The system that biologists use is called binomial nomenclature, because
the international name of a species consists of two words. An example is
Linnaea borealis
(gure 2). The rst name is the genus name. A genus is
a group of species that share certain characteristics. The second name
is the species or specic name. There are various rules about binomial
nomenclature:
The genus name begins with an upper-case (capital) letter and the
species name with a lower-case (small) letter.
In typed or printed text, a binomial is shown in italics.
After a binomial has been used once in a piece of text, it can be
abbreviated to the initial letter of the genus name with the full
species name, for example:
L. borealis
The earliest published name for a species, from 1753 onwards for
plants or 1758 for animals, is the correct one.

Taxonomists lassify speies using a hierarhy of taxa.
The word taxon is Greek and means a group of something. The plural is
taxa. In biology, species are arranged or classied into taxa. Every species
is classied into a genus. Genera are grouped into families. An example
of the genera and species in a family is shown in gure 3. Families are
grouped into orders, orders into classes and so on up to the level of
kingdom or domain. The taxa form a hierarchy, as each taxon includes
taxa from the level below. Going up the hierarchy, the taxa include larger
and larger numbers of species, which share fewer and fewer features.

All organisms are lassied into three domains.
Traditional classication systems have recognized two major categories
of organisms based on cell types: eukaryotes and prokaryotes. This
classication is now regarded as inappropriate because the prokaryotes
have been found to be very diverse. In particular, when the base
sequence of ribosomal RNA was determined, it became apparent that
there are two distinct groups of prokaryotes. They were given the names
Eubacteria and Archaea.
Most classication systems therefore now recognize three major categories
of organism, Eubacteria, Archaea and Eukaryota. These categories are
called domains, so all organisms are classied into three domains. Table 1
shows some of the features that can be used to distinguish between them.
Members of the domains are usually referred to as bacteria, archaeans
and eukaryotes. Bacteria and eukaryotes are relatively familiar to most
biologists but archaeans are often less well known.
